      "options": {
        "mode": "markdown",
        "content": "## v0.9 — IPC over capabilities\n\nTwo userspace processes rendezvous over a capability-gated synchronous endpoint (`workload=ipc`). The **headline** is the cross-process span trace: the **Traces** panel below lists traces named `ipc.*` — click one to open the tree, where you'll see\n\n```\nipc.send      (thread.name = ipc_sender)   ← process A\n└─ ipc.recv   (thread.name = ipc_receiver) ← process B\n```\n\n`ipc.recv` is a **child** of `ipc.send` even though they live in different processes — the kernel populated the trace context across the rendezvous. The `thread.name` attribute (from the `ThreadRegister` frames) is what tells you they're distinct processes.\n\nThe demo sends **one** message, so the trace appears **once** shortly after boot and then the counters hold steady. To run it: `cargo xtask stack up`, then `cargo xtask boot --workload ipc` and `cargo xtask collect` in two terminals."
      }
    },
    {
